<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmi:id="-1Ry-eWIMWFw_tISf7xrAxg" name=",_Ix84IL-PEd2e1-cAeXIm5A" guid="-1Ry-eWIMWFw_tISf7xrAxg" changeDate="2008-12-01T11:03:00.756+0100">
  <mainDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>This task is quite similar for all the enterprises which will develop services compositions. It would be useful to identify which requirements have a direct impact on the architecture of the composition to predict future changes.&lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P>&#xD;
&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>The result of this task is a relevant requirements list which could enhance the knowledge base, including more information about patterns, when to use them and how they can be affected by user requirements. &lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></mainDescription>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUga8HrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Obtain system requirements " guid="_UBUga8HrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>First, gather all the information about system requirements which will be provided by the customer. Try to gather as much information as possible, so the solution will be very close to the usersâ€™ needs and expectations. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgasHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Extract requirements relevant to architecture decisions " guid="_UBUgasHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>With all the information, extract those requirements which might affect the architecture of the system. Try to find out if there are requirements which add restrictions to the architecture because of the way to do something. The application domain and the nature of the composition may be important aspects to have in mind. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_UBUgbMHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw" name="Analyse how requirements affect the architecture " guid="_UBUgbMHrEd2B2LAvnwDruw">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;P class=MsoNormal style=&quot;MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt&quot;>&lt;SPAN style=&quot;mso-ansi-language: EN-US&quot;>&lt;FONT size=3>&lt;FONT face=&quot;Times New Roman&quot;>Using the list of identified requirements relevant to the composition architecture definition, analyse how might affect the architecture each one. The analysis should indicate if changes in the requirements would require an evolution or changes in the architecture. &lt;?xml:namespace prefix = o ns = &quot;urn:schemas-microsoft-com:office:office&quot; />&lt;o:p>&lt;/o:p>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/FONT>&lt;/SPAN>&lt;/P></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
